NetworkX¶

  • creation, manipulation, and study of the structure, dynamics, and function of complex networks.
  • Load and store networks in standard and nonstandard data formats,
  • generate many types of random and classic networks,
  • analyze network structure,
  • build network models, design new network algorithms, draw networks, and much more.

Library documentation: https://networkx.github.io/¶

In [1]:
import networkx as nx
%matplotlib inline

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

G.add_edge(*e)

G.add_edges_from(l)

Graph Operations¶

  • subgraph(G, nbunch) - induce subgraph of G on nodes in nbunch
  • union(G1,G2) - graph union
  • disjoint_union(G1,G2) - graph union assuming all nodes are different
  • cartesian_product(G1,G2) - return Cartesian product graph
  • compose(G1,G2) - combine graphs identifying nodes common to both
  • complement(G) - graph complement
  • create_empty_copy(G) - return an empty copy of the same graph class
  • convert_to_undirected(G) - return an undirected representation of G
  • convert_to_directed(G) - return a directed representation of G
In [57]:
B232 = nx.complete_multipartite_graph(2,3,2)
sub = nx.subgraph(B232, (0,1,2,3,6))
nx.draw_networkx(sub, pos=nx.circular_layout(sub))
In [65]:
C3, C5 = nx.cycle_graph(3), nx.cycle_graph(5)
u35 = nx.union(C3, C5, rename=('3-', '5-'))
nx.draw_networkx(u35, node_color='pink',node_size=450, node_shape='s', pos=nx.circular_layout(u35))
In [69]:
C3, C5 = nx.cycle_graph(3), nx.cycle_graph(5)
u35 = nx.disjoint_union(C3, C5)
nx.draw_networkx(u35, node_color='orange',node_size=450, node_shape='s', pos=nx.circular_layout(u35))
In [97]:

cart23 = nx.cartesian_product(C2, C3)
nx.draw_networkx(cart23, node_color='pink',node_size=750, node_shape='h', pos=nx.circular_layout(cart23))
In [88]:
import itertools
e = itertools.combinations(range(4,7),2)

G, H = nx.Graph(e), nx.complete_graph(5)
comp = nx.compose(G, H)
nx.draw_networkx(comp, node_color='orange',node_size=550, node_shape='s', pos=nx.circular_layout(comp))
In [89]:
